node.text: Here’s a sample of the fantastic seisiún we had yesterday. We were lucky enough to get a full eight hours of this over the course of the day. We’re also delighted to have the lads back for the Sunday seisiún, starting this weekend. Thanks to everyone who came along yesterday, and thanks also to all of you who followed the live stream and sent us messages throughout the day. Now there’s only one thing for it. Get that flight booked for next year!

What kind of mood are you in today? Bright, romantic and nostalgic – or resentful, bitter and twisted? Oh. Well, never mind. Anyway, however you’e feeling, we’ve got the soundtrack to go with it. Over on our site you can stream the fantastic, award-winning Jeff Campbell performing acoustic versions of 14 of Sean’s story songs free. Or, have a look around and you’ll find five whole albums of tracks for download. So you’ll find something, whatever mood you’re in. Let us know.

node.text:
And now for some good news. The orders are flying in and out at the merch store – tee shirts, books, bags, hoodies and beanies, poker cards and of course, the big favorite, the Irish Coffee kit.

There are only two more days of guaranteed delivery before Christmas, so get your order in today or tomorrow at the latest. (We will of course still be sending out orders until the 24th and then again after Christmas Day.)

And though the bar closes again after today, we’ll still be offering our to-go food and drink menus for collection or delivery between 5pm and 10pm, Tuesdays through to Sundays. 

We fight on. No rest for the Rabbit.

node.text:
The great singer Liam Clancy died on this day in 2009. But what a life he led, and what a legacy he left.

Liam had ambitions to be an actor, and while he was pursuing that dream off Broadway in the late 1950s, he was honing another skill, as an interpreter of classic Irish songs – love songs, rebel songs, drinking songs. 
Liam was an intensely charismatic performer, as you can see here as he sings the beautiful ballad 'Ar Éirinn Ní Neosfainn Cé Hí’ (For Ireland I'd Not Tell Her Name). And even if you don’t understand a word, you understand everything. That’s the mark of greatness right there.

We’ve had a lot of enquiries about the beautiful song featured in last week’s clip from Betrothed, the play by Sean’s late mother Kate Muldoon. Here is the song in its 6-minute entirety. 
Many people thought the piece, called Mother, My Dear, was created specially for the play, but it was actually one of many written about 25 years ago by Sean himself. Before the play project came together he had the song re-recorded earlier this year by singer Ashley Davis. Betrothed director Matthew McElhinney felt it was a perfect fit for a play about love and loss and incorporated it throughout the piece. (By the way, discussions are already underway to stage Betrothed again in Belfast and possibly Dublin next year. More details on that soon.) If you’d like a copy of Mother, My Dear, it’ll be on an entire album of Sean’s work called DarkSongs that we’re launching on our site next week.

Here’s a short clip from the dress rehearsal of Betrothed by Sean’s late mother Kate Muldoon, which was staged last week in Belfast’s Grand Opera House. The show was a huge success, and huge credit goes to the fantastic cast, director, producer and technical crew who put it all together in just a couple of weeks. 
Many thanks to everyone who came – especially those old friends who travelled a long way to support the show. 
Now, you may be wondering about that hauntingly beautiful song at the end of the clip. We’ll tell you more about that very soon…

We’re looking forward to seeing lots of old friends on the 15th and 16th of next month at the Grand Opera House in Belfast for the production of Betrothed, by Kate Muldoon.

We’re holding a drinks reception in the theater each night, with @jillianvose serving ticket-holders a complimentary Dead Rabbit Irish Coffee before the curtain goes up – plus our special Heartbreak Punch in the intermission.

Here’s a video we put together where she explains how it’s all done. Remember to turn up the sound.

Tickets are selling very fast indeed, so if you haven’t got yours yet, you could miss out on a great cocktail as well as a great night at the theatre. Double whammy.

Click the Grand Opera House website for availability (http://www.goh.co.uk/)

If you’re feeling a bit squeamish, you probably shouldn't read on. And you definitely shouldn’t click to – uh-oh.

This is the trailer for our Dead Rabbit movie project. Yes, it’s dark and brutal and gritty – just like the story we’re telling, of Irish gang leader John Morrissey reborn as The Rabbit in crime-ridden 1970s NYC.

The trailer is part of the package we’re currently sending out to production companies. We’re confident we’ll find the right partners to make this happen. Because it is going to happen.

Just a matter of time, that’s all.

He’s been illustrated in our menus. Paraded on tee shirts. Featured in photographs and on posters. Starred in videos we’ve made. He’s all over social media (and has his own Instagram account). He turns up at live events. He’s even got an action figure on the way.

Yes, the reborn fighting spirit of Dead Rabbit gang leader John Morrissey has been busy these last few years. But now that we’ve decided we want to make a movie about him, he’s going to get busier still. Much busier.

Stay tuned, folks.

Here’s the promised follow-up to Friday’s post on Sean and Jack’s appearance on local TV in Belfast. The program was UTV Life and the guys were interviewed by Pamela Ballantine.

In just over five minutes Pamela steered the conversation from the history of the bar and the story behind From Barley to Blarney to the state of the Irish whiskey industry and the local cocktail scene – before discussing the lads’ support for the local mental health charity AwareNI.

And that, folks, is how it’s done.

node.text: Our building has seen a lot of history. It’s part of the Fraunces Tavern Historical Block – a group of buildings constructed between 1827 and 1833 and the oldest block in Manhattan. (The Tavern itself was a regular haunt of George Washington.) Our building is of course protected, and much of the original brickwork remains intact after more than 190 years, along with the upper-floor sills and lintels. It all makes for a powerful contrast with the modern glass and steel towers that surround us. We like it that way.

node.text:
The subject of @jillianvose’s latest blog here is our signature drink, the Irish Coffee. It’s a story with some wrong turns, some mistakes, and one or two bright ideas as well. Thoughtfully and expertly prepared, the Irish Coffee can be truly exceptional: we’ve always believed that. Jillian’s article details the  journey of our own version. It took us a while, and there were a few twists and turns along the way. But we think we got there in the end – right?

‘Divilment’ is a great Irish-English word that means mischief, misbehavior or general rascality. And for some reason it immediately springs to mind for our friend Laura as she watches Erin work through the making of the Kill Devil cocktail in today’s new how-to video over on our YouTube channel. What was it about the combination of various rums, sherry, juices and syrup that brought it to mind? It’s hard to tell. But this much we do know: everyone enjoys a little glass of mischief now and again.

Link to full video in profile. And please remember to subscribe to our channel for more fun videos.

node.text:
The last in our series on Ireland’s six best Irish Coffees takes us way up a mountain to Glencullen, County Dublin, and the experience that is Johnnie Fox’s – a destination pub, heavily focused on tourist trade. And everything it does, it does exceptionally well, including its Irish Coffee. They use their own Johnnie Fox’s blended Irish whiskey; strong, freshly brewed coffee; Demerara sugar and cream lightly whipped to the perfect consistency. It’s absolutely delicious, and well worth climbing a mountain for. By the way, if you enjoyed this series, we’re following it with the best Irish Coffees in the US. So watch this space.

Photo by @buda.photography

node.text: Wishes. Amigos. Stooges. So many memorable things come in threes. And this Irish Whiskey trilogy is our own modest contribution. From Barley to Blarney is a love letter to Ireland and to all things uisce beatha. Out next Spring, Paddy Drinks is a fresh take on Irish whiskey cocktails, while When Whiskey Met Its Match – also published next year – tells the definitive story of the greatest Paddy Drink of them all, the Irish Coffee. The power of three? Yip, it’s a real thing.

node.text: This is the first R&D session for our new Taproom menu, which we’ll be launching at the end of September. We are very pleased by standard of new ideas being presented,  including Matt’s riff on a Mai Tai (seen here), using an Asian-inspired orgeat and crème de banane; and a carbonated freshly pressed pear juice with fennel vodka. Now, we all love the Summer, but to be honest right now we just can’t wait for Fall.

node.text: Kavanagh’s, The Long Hall, The Palace Bar. These were three stellar pints we had in Dublin that inspired us to keep working to improve ours. (We wrote a blog recently all about it on our website.) We’ve obsessed over every aspect, but of course, all that really matters is what’s in the glass in front of you. So could you get a better pint than ours? Maybe. But it’d be 3000 miles from here.

node.text: Tomorrow and Wednesday we’ll be at one of the key events of the bar world calendar, and we’re very excited. Bar Convent Brooklyn 2021 is back in the real world after last year’s digital version. We’re looking forward to discovering some new spirit brands, catching a talk or two, some demonstrations and tastings – and of course the chance to catch up with friends, especially after the past year. We’ll be taking part along with Bushmills to present our Irish Coffee. If you’re going to be there, swing by and we’ll make you one. Sound good? You know it.

node.text: When we were growing up, the image of the Sacred Heart seemed to be in every Irish home. Ours was signed and blessed by a Father James Kearney in  1957. We don’t know who he was but we do know how the picture came to be here. Sean had asked his mother Kate to find one for the bar and she spotted it in a garage sale as she and Sean’s dad were driving past. She asked how much it was. “No charge for holy pictures, it’s free” was the answer. And so here it is, 3,000 miles away and 64 years later.

Today on Saturday Movie Club we’ve got… another punch for you. This one, which we’ve cleverly called Punch and Judy (geddit?) is up on our YouTube channel now. In it you’ll see Erin in a thrilling race again time – and against a barrage of corny jokes from Laura – to assemble velvet falernum, cachaça, manuka flower tea-infused gin and lemon sherbet into the magical elixir. Will she make it? (Yeah, of course she will, she’s Erin.) Get the popcorn ready and settle in.

Link to full video in profile.

node.text:
Today we’re in Kerry for the fifth stop in our series on the best Irish Coffees we’ve found in Ireland. Now, Dick Mack’s in Dingle does not serve coffee. It serves something much, much better. They start with a freshly roasted coffee blend made specially for them just down the street. It goes perfectly with Powers, the preferred whiskey. The coffee is filter-brewed in the bar and mixed with a little Demerara sugar. The whiskey is added to the warmed glass and lightly whipped cream is poured over the top. And the result is, well, extraordinary. Try it. You’ll see.

Photo by @buda.photography

node.text: Here’s our latest menu addition: Tuna Tartare Tacos. What you’re looking at is a serving of four individual tacos packed with our tuna tartare mix – no. 1 tuna, chipotle puree, lime zest, cilantro and olive oil. We serve these on a bed of avocado puree and top them with micro cilantro. And of course, there’s a lime wedge to add a little extra zestiness. So, what do you think? Tempted? Yeah, we thought so.
